After parting ways with Hinata and the others, I visited the ruins of the mountain hut, and found that the old wood and paper burned particularly well.

Behind them were the remains of a sooty stone hearth and an underground storehouse.

I searched the ruins, but the cloth bag containing the coins the elf had given me was nowhere to be found.

Apparently, the villagers had searched the hut and stolen anything of value before setting it on fire.

I had nowhere to go back to so I returned to my house in the village, but I wish I hadn't.

Perhaps because they feel guilty about stealing my things, the villagers look at me more strangely than before.

It's strange that the person who had something stolen from would be glared at by the thief.

"...You have no attachment to this village anymore, right?"

Maybe I should just set fire to this house too.

That thought crosses my mind.

If the house were to burn on a windy day, even if it was on the outskirts of the village, the fire could spread to other places and cause a terrible disaster.

If that happens, I wonder if I'll feel a little better?

But I didn't choose that.

...I didn't care about anything anymore.

There was no way I, an indecisive person who couldn’t even take Hinata’s hand back then, could choose to do something as bold as setting fire to a house.

The only thing I can do is run away.

Just like that day when we fled from the village into the forest.

