It's a time when it's okay to feel a little cheerful as you set off on your journey.

I crossed the village and my thoughts turned to the dark forest.

Ibara said that it was because of me that the path of humanity was paved.

So this journey is for the elves.

In order to break away from the path of humanity, I will not return to the forest, but will leave my original village and travel far away.

The noble cause of doing it for the sake of the elves is incredibly satisfying.

I know that this was really just an escape, but I needed a good excuse for myself.

This place, this village, that forest, there are so many memories.

My weakness, my indecisiveness, tormented me everywhere.

I know very well that running away won't change anything.

So run away, just somewhere other than here.

Ibara asked me if that was okay. Hinata's voice reached out to me as we parted ways.

No, not just then.

I made no effort to fit in with the people around me, and instead tried to maintain my sense of self by looking down on them.

Valuable records were set on fire as a result.

I'm running away from everything I've lost.

The only person who lies ahead of me will surely be me, a nobody.

That's fine.

It would be better to live my life being chased by my worthless self than to face my pathetic past here, in this village.

Will I ever find my place?

If there had been some attempt to change, would it have been possible to do so?

That day will probably never come, but I'm sure that the memories I let go of will one day be beautifully colored to suit my needs.

That's how I continue to live, deceiving myself. Until the day I lose my life, I will continue to live in vain. Not here. In a place where those happy days are out of reach.

He will always live with regret that he wasn't able to hold Hinata's hand back then.

I'm sure that's my punishment for not being able to make any choice until the very end.


